                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-154181 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-sex-crimes des-sex-crimes news_keywords-rape-2" id="post-154181">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">On Johnny&#x2019;s Knee</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Rene Denfeld			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-09-17T22:53:52+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">September 17, 2014 6:53 pm</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">September 17, 2014 6:53 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/09/17/on-johnnys-knee/" data-title="Private Lives: On Johnny&#x2019;s Knee"
                                        data-description="Grown, with children of my own, I still dreamed of the abuser I once thought of as my father.">
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My phone pinged. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I knew instantly what the alert was, because the heading is always the same. I had signed up for a criminal notification system to keep tabs on the man I called my father. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> &#x201C;This email is to inform you that the offender Johnny Hill has been arrested and placed in custody.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> That&#x2019;s my dad, I thought: predatory sex offender. <span id="more-154181"></span></p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/18/opinion/0918PRIVATELIVES/0918PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject"
                                            role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/18/opinion/0918PRIVATELIVES/0918PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/18/opinion/0918PRIVATELIVES/0918PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg"
                                                    id="100000003121350" width="480" height="615" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="615">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> J&#xE9;r&#xF4;me Dubois</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I was about 4 when Johnny came into our lives. He was a pimp. He saved us from an even worse pimp named Lane, who beat my mother bloody. Johnny took us to his home. I sat in his lap, a tiny girl with Botticelli curls.
                                        Johnny smelled like Pink hair lotion and Jheri curl activator. He wore a hat with a feather.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">During the days, Johnny took me into a bar on what was then Union Avenue in Portland, Ore. The women, dancing in cages in full-length nylon body stockings, mesmerized me. At night our house became crowded with prostitutes,
                                        all skin and eyes. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I loved Johnny. He fathered my younger brother and sister. He taught me how to put hot sauce on rotten fish to make it taste better. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But life with Johnny was fraught with terror, too &#x2014; men kicking in the front door with sawed-off shotguns, holding their guns to our heads because Johnny owed them money. And my poor mother, stumbling home after
                                        being raped on the streets, my big brother washing her tenderly in the bathtub. She said later that she had been out looking for Johnny. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At nights I slept with Johnny and my mother. The other kids got to sleep on a mattress down the hall. I was never told why I had to share his bed. I tried desperately to avoid going to bed, by hiding in the closet,
                                        crawling in the dirt under the house, peeing myself. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> What happened in that bed? I cannot remember now, and have never remembered. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I can remember when Johnny went to prison. I was in the courtroom when he was sentenced. My mom said he was convicted of robbing someone at gunpoint. I have no idea if that was true. The last I saw of him was his slender
                                        back as they led him away. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Except in my dreams.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I went on to become a journalist and to adopt three kids from foster care. I took a day job, working as a death penalty investigator. I am hired by the lawyers representing men and women facing execution to examine
                                        their backgrounds in hopes of persuading a judge or jury to extend them mercy. It is the gift of my history that I can understand these people and their families. I can see their humanity even as I witness the harm
                                        they have done to others, and the harm done to them. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> But part of me was forever suspended on Johnny&#x2019;s knee. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">How could I move on? He was the father of my younger siblings. He was responsible, in part, for the suicide of my dear older brother, who eventually lost faith in the power of tenderness, and took his own life. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> And every few months came the ping on the phone. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> &#x201C;Approaches female strangers as they are getting into their parked cars,&#x201D; reads his sex offender notification sheet. &#x201C;He drives them to isolated locations with the intent of raping and robbing them.
                                        Uses weapons, threats and physical abuse to gain compliance.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> You might think that someone like that would be kept in prison. But Johnny is made of Teflon. He is always released: &#x201C;Conditions and restrictions: Anger management treatment. Attend sex offender treatment, polygraph,
                                        plethysmograph testing. No alcohol. No drug paraphernalia or association with known drug users. No contact with victim or minors.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When warrants were out for Johnny my nightmares became florid. Knowing he was wandering the streets sent me into terror. I still lived in North Portland, in a neighborhood not far from where I grew up. I dreamed he
                                        was under the fir trees outside my window. Even after decades, the watery feeling of recognition in my legs was real. I dreamed he broke into the house and came swaying, like a serpent, into my room. In my worst
                                        nightmares he was in the bedrooms of my children. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Finally I had had enough. When I got a ping that he had been arrested &#x2014; again &#x2014; I went to talk to my therapist. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;I want to talk to him,&#x201D; I told her. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> She&#x2019;s a good therapist. She only nodded. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A few days later I was talking to Johnny, on the jailhouse phone. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> He was cautious. He didn&#x2019;t want to admit to knowing me. I told him we had lived with him; he had saved us from Lane. I talked about my mom. She had died four years before, still unwilling to talk about Johnny.
                                        </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> &#x201C;I was a lot of places back then,&#x201D; he chuckled. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I was thunderstruck. Was it possible he didn&#x2019;t even remember us? That we were just faceless numbers in a long catalog of victims? </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> But now Johnny had an audience. He told me he was getting his act together, he had lost his teeth but was getting new ones, &#x201C;because it&#x2019;s all about presentation,&#x201D; you know. He kept talking until
                                        I actually started feeling bored. Right, Johnny, I thought, as he droned on in his slushy old man voice. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I realized then that Johnny had ended up right where he belonged: a toothless old man in a county jail. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I could beat you up, I thought. I had a vision of breaking every bone in his body with a hammer. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Johnny wanted to keep talking, but I was done. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> That night I went outside. It was dark. I stepped under the fir trees in the side yard and looked up at my window, a warm beacon of light. My children are in that house, I thought. I am keeping them safe. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> A few months ago came yet another ping. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Johnny had talked another judge into releasing him into a treatment program. Sure enough, he escaped. Another warrant was out for his arrest. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> &#x201C;This email is to inform you that there has been a change in the custody status of the offender Johnny Hill &#x2026; A warrant for the offender&#x2019;s arrest is now active.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> He is wandering the streets again, I thought. He could be outside right now.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> But this time I wasn&#x2019;t afraid. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I used to love you, Johnny, I thought. I don&#x2019;t love you anymore. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> He was not my father. He never had been. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I said a prayer that night, for his victims, and for any woman unlucky enough to encounter him on the streets. And then I said a prayer for my mother, dead and gone, carrying her raft of pain with her. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I haven&#x2019;t dreamed of him since. </p>
                                    <hr>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//www.renedenfeld.com/ ">Rene Denfeld</a> is the author of the novel &#x201C;The Enchanted.&#x201D;</em></p>
                                </div>
                                <footer class="entry-footer">
